<article>
    <h1>BMW Def&#xAD;i&#xAD;ni&#xAD;tion CE4 re&#xAD;de&#xAD;fines scooter styling</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201121/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-21"><time>2020-11-21</time></a>
        - <span>MOTORING | LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The BMW Def­i­ni­tion CE4 (right) is an elec­tric scooter with a flat bat­tery pack in its un­der­floor. Com­bined with a com­pact driv­e­train, it al­lows BMW to break from tra­di­tional scooter styling and also frees up space for a lit stor­age com­part­ment which can be ac­cessed from the side.</p>
    <p>The po­si­tion of the bat­tery pack cre­ates a low cen­tre of grav­ity, which en­hances han­dling.</p>
    <p>The scooter’s pan­els do not com­pletely cover the side sec­tion at the rear. In­stead, they stretch across parts of the ve­hi­cle’s side like lit­tle wings al­low­ing views of the drive unit, cool­ing ribs, sin­gle-sided swing arm, spring strut and tooth belt. The 10.25-inch dis­play is the largest in the scooter seg­ment.</p>

